&gt;&gt;Re: code that throws exceptions. I prefer to declare the test case as
&gt;&gt;throwing the exception. I haven&#39;t ever had trouble debugging from the
&gt;&gt;information provided in the exception. Discarding that exception and getting
&gt;&gt;a generic AssertionError seems a step backwards to me.
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; How often have you wished your test verified data stored in the expected 
&gt; exception? Ever? This is the one bit that surprises me, because I often 
&gt; want to check more than merely catching an instanceof the expected type. 
&gt; Can you think of a time when you would have preferred, in retrospect, to 
&gt; have checked more than just the exception type?

This is an important point. For example, what if you have a method that 
will throw an IllegalArgumentException if any of its three arguments is 
null? It&#39;s all well and good to have three separate test cases targeting 
each of the three arguments, but it&#39;s rather sloppy to have your tests 
simply catch the expected IllegalArgumentException without checking its 
message to determine /which/ of the arguments caused it.

My solution to this is twofold:

1) Use a utility class (called ArgChecker) with static methods that will 
test arguments for null, negative values, mismatched class types, etc., 
and will throw IllegalArgumentExceptions with appropriate messages. For 
example,

in the ArgChecker class:
     public static void throwIfNull(Object arg, String description);
       if (arg == null) {
	throw new IllegalArgumentException(
           /* generate message from description (see below) */);
       }
     }

in the Foo class:
     public Foo(String type, int index) {
       ArgChecker.throwIfNull(type, &quot;initial type&quot;);
                       // msg = &quot;The initial type cannot be null&quot;
       this.type = type;
       ArgChecker.throwIfNegative(index, &quot;initial index&quot;);
                       // msg = &quot;The initial index cannot be negative&quot;
       this.idx = index;
     }

2) I have test utility that test methods use to check the exception 
messages for the expected value.

in the FooTest class:
   public void test_ctor_nullType() {
     String type = null;
     int index = 99;
     try {
       new Foo(type, index);
       fail(&quot;Should reject a null type&quot;);
     } catch (IllegalArgumentException iax) {
       IllegalArgumentAssert.assertNullMessage(&quot;initial type&quot;);
     }

This second part introduces some admittedly shaky dependencies between 
the ArgChecker, the IllegalArgumentAssert, and the class under test:

* the IllegalArgumentAssert has to know the exact text of the 
exception&#39;s message, as generated by the ArgChecker. I get away with 
this by storing the ArgChecker&#39;s messages in a boilerplate properties 
file with publicly-scoped property keys.
* the Foo test method has to know the descriptions that Foo passes to 
the ArgChecker&#39;s methods. I /don&#39;t/ expose these as public constants on 
Foo, just because that seems like more work than it has to be, and 
because any subsequent change that someone may make to Foo&#39;s 
descriptions will quickly fail the relevant test(s) and should be easy 
for the developer to fix.
